ols from disciplines such as film studies and cognitive science that allow the reader to establish how a fictional narrative is built, how it functions, and how it defines the boundaries of concepts that appear susceptible to limitless interpretations. Aldama emphasizes how postcolonial and Latino borderland narrative fiction authors and artists use narrative devices to create their aesthetic blueprints in ways that loosely guide their readers' imagination and emotion. In A User's Guide to Postcolonial and Latino Borderland Fiction, he argues that the study of ethnic-identified narrative fiction must acknowledge its active engagement with world narrative fictional genres, storytelling modes, and techniques, as well as the way such fictions work to move their audiences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aAmerican fictionxMexican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aCommonwealth fiction (English)xHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish fictionxMinority authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aFictionxHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aNarration (Rhetoric). 0aPostcolonialism in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / Hispanic American.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292799172423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292799172/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK